    body: "Losing a spouse is one of the hardest experiences anyone can face, and the paperwork that follows can feel overwhelming when grief is fresh. One of the first calls many surviving spouses are asked to make is to the Social Security Administration. This call matters because Social Security needs to know in order to stop your late spouse's monthly benefits, begin a small one-time death payment of $255 for eligible survivors, and start the process for any ongoing survivor benefits you may qualify for. Doing nothing can lead to overpayments that the government will later ask you to return, sometimes months after the fact, which adds stress at a time when you do not need any more of it.\n\nThe good news is that you do not have to do this alone. In most cases the funeral home you use will offer to report the death to Social Security as part of their services. Many funeral directors will ask for your late spouse's Social Security number and handle the first notification for you. That said, even when the funeral home reports the death, you should still follow up with Social Security on your own to confirm the report went through and to start the survivor benefit conversation. Funeral home reports stop the benefit but they do not enroll you in anything new.\n\nThis guide walks you through who to call, what papers to have ready, what to expect during the call, and how to apply for survivor benefits if you are eligible. The tone here is meant to be warm. You are grieving. You can take this in small pieces. Doing one step today and another step tomorrow is perfectly fine. The Social Security Administration is used to working with people in your situation, and the representatives on the phone are trained to be patient and kind.\n\nGather these documents before you call: your late spouse's full legal name, Social Security number, date of birth, date of death, and the name and address of the funeral home. If you can, find a certified copy of the death certificate — the funeral home usually provides several copies at no extra charge, and you will want at least five to ten copies for banks, insurance, and other accounts. You will also need your own Social Security number, your marriage certificate, and any divorce decrees if either of you was married before. Take your time gathering these. There is no penalty for waiting a week or two while you find them.",
