    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "When a spouse passes away, the Social Security Administration offers ongoing monthly payments called survivor benefits to the surviving widow or widower. These payments can be a meaningful part of your monthly income for the rest of your life, often replacing some of what the household lost when one Social Security check stopped coming in. As of 2026, the average monthly survivor benefit for an aged widow or widower is about $1,775, though your own amount depends on what your late spouse earned during their working years.\n\nUnderstanding survivor benefits matters because the timing of when you apply can change how much you receive every month for years to come. Take a benefit at age 60 and it will be reduced; wait until your full retirement age (66 to 67 depending on the year you were born) and you receive 100 percent of what your spouse was entitled to. Many widows and widowers also have their own work history and can choose between their personal Social Security retirement benefit and the survivor benefit. In many cases, the smart strategy is to take one early and switch to the other at a later age to get the larger lifetime payout. This is one of the few places in the Social Security system where you actually have a strategic choice, and Social Security representatives can help you compare amounts without pressuring you to decide on the spot.\n\nThis guide walks you through who qualifies, what papers to bring, how to apply, and the key questions to ask the Social Security representative so you do not leave money on the table. It also covers the special rules for divorced surviving spouses (yes, you may still qualify) and for those caring for a child of the deceased. Take this guide in pieces. You can read about eligibility today, gather papers tomorrow, and make the appointment when you feel ready. There is no deadline that will cause you to lose your survivor benefit forever — though waiting too long can mean missed monthly payments that the government will not pay retroactively beyond six months in most cases.\n\nMany surviving spouses worry that asking about money will feel cold or improper so soon after a loss. Please set that worry aside. Social Security benefits are something your spouse paid into for decades through every paycheck. Claiming them is honoring the work they did to take care of you. The representatives at Social Security have these conversations every single day with people in your exact situation, and they know how to handle them with care.",
